\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Deviation Thresholds and Corrective Action Protocol
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Not all SLA deviations require the same response.
 This section establishes the thresholds at which a deviation escalates from a work order management issue to a documented operational deficiency requiring formal action,
 and defines the required response at each threshold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Threshold 1 — Individual Breach (Operational Response)
\series default
:
 A single SLA Breach shall trigger a breach review by the Assistant IT Director within one (1) business hour of breach detection.
 The Assistant IT Director shall document the cause in the work order record and determine whether the breach resulted from (a) resource or workload conditions,
 (b) a process or triage failure,
 (c) a vendor response gap,
 or (d) an approved exception.
 No formal corrective action plan is required for an isolated breach,
 but the Assistant IT Director shall retain the cause documentation and count it toward threshold calculations below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Threshold 2 — Severity-Weighted Breach Rate (Formal Review)
\series default
:
 When the SLA breach rate for any individual severity level exceeds ten percent (10%) of all work orders at that severity level within any rolling thirty (30) calendar day period,
 the Assistant IT Director shall initiate a formal review.
 The Assistant IT Director shall document the formal review in writing,
 complete it within five (5) business days of threshold detection,
 and submit it to the IT Director.
 The review shall identify systemic causes,
 affected services or personnel,
 and recommended remediation.
 The IT Director shall approve or direct modifications to the recommended remediation within five (5) business days of receipt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Threshold 3 — Sustained Non-Compliance (Corrective Action Plan)
\series default
:
 When a formal review under Threshold 2 identifies the same root cause for the second consecutive thirty (30) calendar day period,
 or when the breach rate for any severity level exceeds twenty percent (20%) in any single thirty (30) calendar day period,
 the Assistant IT Director shall initiate a formal Corrective Action Plan (CAP) under 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:5.03"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Compliance Monitoring and Corrective Action).
 The Assistant IT Director shall assign the CAP,
 submit it to the IT Director for approval,
 and track it to closure.
 The Assistant IT Director shall report open CAPs in the Monthly Performance Summary Report defined in Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Vendor-Specific Deviation
\series default
:
 When a vendor governing an IT-Supported asset fails to meet contracted SLA terms and the failure results in an IT breach of the referral or escalation commitment defined in 
\series bold
Policy 
